\section*{Problem}

An electron moves in a circle of radius \SI{1.9}{\meter} in a magnetic field of \SI{3e-5}{\tesla}. Calculate (a) the speed of the electron and (b) the time taken to move around the circle.

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Speed of the Electron}

The force acting on the electron due to the magnetic field is the centripetal force required to keep it moving in a circle. The magnetic force is given by:

\[
F = qvB
\]

where \( q \) is the charge of the electron (\( q = -1.6 \times 10^{-19} \, \mathrm{C} \)), \( v \) is the speed of the electron, and \( B \) is the magnetic field.

The centripetal force is given by:

\[
F = \frac{mv^2}{r}
\]

where \( m \) is the mass of the electron (\( m = 9.11 \times 10^{-31} \, \mathrm{kg} \)) and \( r \) is the radius of the circle.

Equating the magnetic force to the centripetal force:

\[
qvB = \frac{mv^2}{r}
\]

Solving for \( v \):

\[
v = \frac{qBr}{m}
\]

Substituting the known values:

\[
v = \frac{(1.6 \times 10^{-19} \, \mathrm{C})(3 \times 10^{-5} \, \mathrm{T})(1.9 \, \mathrm{m})}{9.11 \times 10^{-31} \, \mathrm{kg}}
\]

\[
v \approx 1.0 \times 10^6 \, \mathrm{m/s}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Time Taken to Move Around the Circle}

The time taken to complete one revolution is the circumference of the circle divided by the speed:

\[
T = \frac{2\pi r}{v}
\]

Substituting the known values:

\[
T = \frac{2\pi (1.9 \, \mathrm{m})}{1.0 \times 10^6 \, \mathrm{m/s}}
\]

\[
T \approx 1.2 \times 10^{-5} \, \mathrm{s}
\]

Thus, the speed of the electron is approximately \( 1.0 \times 10^6 \, \mathrm{m/s} \) and the time taken to move around the circle is approximately \( 1.2 \times 10^{-5} \, \mathrm{s} \).

