\section*{Problem}

A cyclotron has a magnetic field of \SI{15000}{G}. The extraction radius is \SI{50}{cm}. Calculate:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The frequency of the RF necessary for accelerating deuterons.
    \item The energy of the extracted beam.
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Frequency of the RF}

The cyclotron frequency (also known as the angular frequency) for a charged particle in a magnetic field is given by:
\[
\omega = \frac{qB}{m}
\]
where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( q \) is the charge of the particle,
    \item \( B \) is the magnetic field strength,
    \item \( m \) is the mass of the particle.
\end{itemize}

For deuterons, \( q = e \) (the elementary charge) and \( m = 2m_p \) (where \( m_p \) is the proton mass).

The frequency \( f \) is related to the angular frequency by:
\[
f = \frac{\omega}{2\pi} = \frac{qB}{2\pi m}
\]

Substituting the given values:
\begin{align*}
B &= \SI{15000}{G} = \SI{1.5}{T} \quad (\text{since } \SI{1}{T} = \SI{10000}{G}) \\
q &= e = \SI{1.602 \times 10^{-19}}{C} \\
m &= 2m_p = 2 \times \SI{1.673 \times 10^{-27}}{kg}
\end{align*}

Thus, the frequency is:
\[
f = \frac{1.602 \times 10^{-19} \times 1.5}{2\pi \times 2 \times 1.673 \times 10^{-27}}
\]

Calculating this gives:
\[
f \approx \SI{11.5}{MHz}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Energy of the Extracted Beam}

The kinetic energy \( K \) of the deuterons at the extraction radius can be calculated using the formula:
\[
K = \frac{1}{2} mv^2
\]

The velocity \( v \) can be found from the centripetal force equation:
\[
qvB = \frac{mv^2}{r} \quad \Rightarrow \quad v = \frac{qBr}{m}
\]

Substituting the given values:
\begin{align*}
r &= \SI{50}{cm} = \SI{0.5}{m} \\
v &= \frac{1.602 \times 10^{-19} \times 1.5 \times 0.5}{2 \times 1.673 \times 10^{-27}}
\end{align*}

Calculating \( v \) and substituting back into the kinetic energy equation:
\[
K = \frac{1}{2} \times 2 \times 1.673 \times 10^{-27} \times \left(\frac{1.602 \times 10^{-19} \times 1.5 \times 0.5}{2 \times 1.673 \times 10^{-27}}\right)^2
\]

Solving this gives:
\[
K \approx \SI{25}{MeV}
\]

\end{document}
