\section*{Dimensional Analysis of Faraday's Law}

Faraday's law is given by:
\[
\mathcal{E} = \frac{d\Phi_B}{dt}
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \(\mathcal{E}\) is the electromotive force (emf) measured in volts (V).
    \item \(\Phi_B\) is the magnetic flux measured in weber (Wb).
    \item \(t\) is time measured in seconds (s).
\end{itemize}

To show that the equation is dimensionally correct, we need to verify that both sides have the same dimensions.

\subsection*{Dimensions of \(\mathcal{E}\)}

The dimension of electromotive force \(\mathcal{E}\) in terms of fundamental units is:
\[
[\mathcal{E}] = [\text{V}] = [\text{ML}^2\text{T}^{-3}\text{I}^{-1}]
\]
where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \([\text{M}]\) is mass,
    \item \([\text{L}]\) is length,
    \item \([\text{T}]\) is time,
    \item \([\text{I}]\) is electric current.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Dimensions of \(\frac{d\Phi_B}{dt}\)}

The dimension of magnetic flux \(\Phi_B\) is:
\[
[\Phi_B] = [\text{Wb}] = [\text{ML}^2\text{T}^{-2}\text{I}^{-1}]
\]

Thus, the dimension of \(\frac{d\Phi_B}{dt}\) is:
\[
\left[\frac{d\Phi_B}{dt}\right] = \frac{[\Phi_B]}{[\text{T}]} = \frac{[\text{ML}^2\text{T}^{-2}\text{I}^{-1}]}{[\text{T}]} = [\text{ML}^2\text{T}^{-3}\text{I}^{-1}]
\]

\subsection*{Conclusion}

Since the dimensions of \(\mathcal{E}\) and \(\frac{d\Phi_B}{dt}\) are both \([\text{ML}^2\text{T}^{-3}\text{I}^{-1}]\), Faraday's law is dimensionally correct.

